/// System-level runtime introspection — version 1.1.0.
///
/// Additive companion to `astrid:sys@1.0.0`, NOT a superset. @1.0.0 mutates
/// nothing and remains the home of the full system surface (logging, config,
/// time, entropy, sleep, capability introspection); a guest keeps importing it
/// for all of that. This package adds a single orthogonal introspection
/// function — `capsule-set-epoch` — with no shared types, so a guest imports
/// @1.1.0 ALONGSIDE @1.0.0 solely to reach the new call. (Contrast
/// `astrid:http@1.1.0`, which is a full superset precisely because it changed
/// existing @1.0.0 record / variant shapes; nothing here does.)
///
/// Astrid does not expose any `wasi:*` interfaces to capsules. The host ABI is
/// fully Astrid-owned: every call is gated, principal-scoped, audited, and
/// dispatched through the kernel's capability layer.
///
/// Frozen per the ABI evolution discipline (RFC: host_abi). Shape changes
/// ship as a new file at a new version path; never edit this file.

package astrid:sys@1.1.0;

interface host {
    /// Return a stable hash of the currently-loaded capsule set — the sorted
    /// `(capsule-id, package-version)` pairs across every registered capsule.
    ///
    /// The value MOVES when a capsule is installed, removed, or version-bumped
    /// (a live upgrade), and is independent of load order. It carries no
    /// process state: an unchanged set hashes identically across daemon
    /// restarts, so a consumer can persist it beside a cache keyed on the
    /// loaded set (e.g. a per-principal tool-schema cache) and re-validate
    /// cheaply on its own next turn — picking up a runtime install without the
    /// kernel fanning an invalidation out to every principal.
    ///
    /// Ungated, read-only introspection like `astrid:sys@1.0.0`'s
    /// `enumerate-capabilities`: the loaded-set fingerprint is structural
    /// metadata, not a secret, and conveys no ability. Infallible by design —
    /// there is no `result` wrapper; if the registry is momentarily
    /// unavailable the host returns `0`, a value that will not match any
    /// populated cache's stored epoch and so biases the consumer toward a
    /// (safe) refresh rather than stale reuse. Audit: not recorded (read-only).
    capsule-set-epoch: func() -> u64;
}
